00:43.880 --> 00:50.960
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. Clifford Simak is a veteran science
fiction writer who has been producing short stories and novels continuously

00:50.960 --> 01:00.520
since 1938. Simak won the International Fantasy Award for his City Series, Hugo
Awards for his stories at the Big Front Yard, and The Grotto of the Dancing

01:00.520 --> 01:09.080
Deer, and the novel Way Station. And he was honored by his peers when they
presented him with the Grandmaster Nebula Award. Simak's prolific output is

01:09.080 --> 01:16.780
remarkable when one learns that until his retirement a few years ago, he was a
full-time newspaper man. We asked him how he decided to become a newspaper man.

01:17.440 --> 01:21.200
There was no decision because I think I always knew what I wanted to write.

01:24.360 --> 01:38.060
And I never really thought of writing fiction or writing books or anything of
that sort. It seemed to me that the way to write was to be a newspaper man. My

01:38.060 --> 01:54.480
mother, who was a very well-educated woman, had books in the house all the time,
and I read them. Despite the fact that we were poor, we got a daily paper. And

01:54.480 --> 02:07.700
she used to sit at the table by the light of a kerosene lamp and read it each
evening after all the work was done. And I asked her at one time, I remember, if

02:07.700 --> 02:21.340
a newspaper carried all the news, printed all the news there was. And she, in
the manner of that day, and because people were not as cynical then as they are

02:21.340 --> 02:34.200
now, said, yes, that was true. And I asked her another question that I thought
was important. I said, is all the news true? Is what the newspaper writes true?

02:34.200 --> 02:45.920
And again, with that lack of cynicism and faith that the people of that time
had, she said, yes, it was. And that decided me, decided me to want to be a

02:45.920 --> 02:56.080
newspaper man. So Simak did become a newspaper man, but eventually he found that
the type of writing it required did not completely satisfy him. We asked him why

02:56.080 --> 03:11.600
he chose science fiction when he decided to write fiction. Well, because when I
was a boy, I had read Jules Verne and I think H.G. Wells, although I don't

03:11.600 --> 03:18.820
actually remember any H.G. Wells works, but I must have read them. Edgar Allan
Poe and Haggard.

03:20.980 --> 03:24.100
And I thought what a wonderful thing that was.

03:26.740 --> 03:36.860
I just had an awful interest in the field. I wanted to read it myself, and I
found out when I decided that I wanted to write, when I found out that newspaper

03:36.860 --> 03:52.100
didn't give me everything that I wanted in the writing field, I decided that on
my spare time I write, I naturally seemed to turn to science fiction, because it

03:52.100 --> 04:02.640
was something I was acquainted with. I felt very sure that I could do the job of
it. And I was quite fortunate, of course, because there was no competition at

04:02.640 --> 04:08.700
that time. If you could string in three sentences together and make a paragraph,
somebody would buy the story.

04:20.820 --> 04:29.100
Simak's combination of professions is, on the surface, a strange mixture. After
all, newspaper writing requires a lean, straightforward type of prose, whereas

04:29.100 --> 04:39.640
fiction requires much fuller writing. We asked Simak if he thought the styles
required are significantly different. They are absolutely upwards. But I

04:39.640 --> 04:47.100
compartmentalized my life into two lives.

04:48.280 --> 05:02.320
When I went to work in the morning, I was a newspaper man. And when I came home
and sat down at my desk at night, I was a fiction writer. More on Clifford Simak

05:02.320 --> 05:03.180
in our next show.

05:10.660 --> 05:18.840
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

05:18.840 --> 05:19.620
Odessa, Texas.

