06:41.220 --> 06:50.800
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Science fiction writer Clifford Simak has
been publishing almost continuously every year since 1938. Right, but Simak's

06:50.800 --> 06:58.840
first stories were published several years earlier. Here he explains how his
writing career got started and how it was temporarily stopped. I started my

06:58.840 --> 07:16.260
newspaper career in 1929, and my first short story appeared in, I think, 1931.
And I wrote, at that time, I wrote several other short stories which were

07:16.260 --> 07:29.520
published. And at about that time, the magazine, all magazines, the science
fiction magazines and all others, ran into hard times because the Great

07:29.520 --> 07:44.040
Depression came along. And so there was no market, practically no market. So I
dropped out and didn't do any more writing, any other fiction writing of any

07:44.040 --> 07:59.320
kind, until I think it was 37 or 38. And I started writing again because the
magazines had come back. John Campbell had been named editor of Astounding. And I

07:59.320 --> 08:17.280
felt fairly sure I could sell my work to John Campbell. So I started writing again.
And I think since 1938 and 1939, I think it's 38, 37 or 38, there was only one

08:17.280 --> 08:28.360
year in which none of my work appeared. There was one year that's blank. And I
can't remember which year that it was, and I have no idea why that occurred.

08:39.920 --> 08:48.720
So Simak became an early mainstay in John W. Campbell's stable of writers at
Astounding Stories. We asked Simak why he thought his work appealed to Campbell.

08:49.360 --> 08:51.480
I'd read a lot of John Campbell's work.

08:57.460 --> 09:05.560
And I knew it. I knew it. John Campbell was favored

09:05.560 --> 09:16.780
what we today call hard science fiction. And I thought that I could write that
kind of science fiction. I did write what amounted to hard science fiction for

09:16.780 --> 09:27.340
some years, and then begin to turn over to the softer science fiction, such most
of which, well, most people write soft science fiction today. Only a few of the

09:27.340 --> 09:32.080
old hands and maybe a few new beginners write the hard science fiction today.

09:39.580 --> 09:48.200
During the first few decades he wrote, Simak produced short stories almost
exclusively. We asked him to tell us why he stuck to the short story form. Short

09:48.200 --> 09:58.460
stories is the trading ground for the novelist. 
You can learn a lot more from writing a short story

09:58.460 --> 10:14.600
than you can writing a novel. It's shorter to write, somewhat easier to write.
You don't have the time invested in a short story to do a novel. If you spend,

10:14.880 --> 10:27.780
as a beginner, probably a six-month-old year writing a novel, and it fails,
well, that's catastrophic. But during that same time, you could write a half a

10:27.780 --> 10:44.260
dozen short stories, and if only one of them sold, well, okay, you have made a
beginning. So it's the path that most people take to becoming writers or long

10:44.260 --> 10:57.160
-going work. And that doesn't apply only to the science fiction field, but to
any literature. More on Clifford Simak on our next show.

