12:22.920 --> 12:24.580
And here are your hosts.

12:29.160 --> 12:36.620
This is Daryl Lane. And Bill Vernon. Science fiction author Clifford Simak has
written numerous short stories and novels, and he has won several awards in the

12:36.620 --> 12:45.780
field. Perhaps Simak's most famous and enduring work is his City Collection, a
series of eight interconnected stories written in the 1940s. These stories

12:45.780 --> 12:54.880
featured mankind's reaction to a new situation, and man's relationship with an
old friend, the dog, and a new one, the robot. Simak agreed when we call these

12:54.880 --> 13:09.820
stories a leap from his previous efforts. It was a leap. Because I
always regard the City stories as a sort of watershed in my writing. I have been

13:09.820 --> 13:27.860
writing the old type of early type science fiction work up until then. And it
seemed to me that there was something better could be done than was being done.

13:28.940 --> 13:42.860
Strangely enough, at about the same time, a number of other people seemed to
think the same thing. There's no accounting for something like that happening.

13:50.600 --> 14:00.860
We asked Simak what influenced him to write these revolutionary stories. I think
it was my disillusion

14:00.860 --> 14:10.740
brought up by the war that made me write the City series.

14:13.660 --> 14:28.400
It seemed to me that we were going through a horrible period in history, and
that much of human dignity had been sheared away, that it was not the kind of

14:28.400 --> 14:44.700
world that we had lived in up until that time. And I found myself wanting to
retreat from it. So I retreated from it mentally by going into another

14:44.700 --> 15:00.840
dimension, into another world, creating a sort of fantasy where myself and, as
it turned out, others also were able to find some refuge. I think if the City

15:00.840 --> 15:16.480
series were written today, that they probably would not get the attention that
they got back in the early 40s. I wrote them exactly the right kind of story at

15:16.480 --> 15:21.580
exactly the right time, without knowing I was doing it.

15:32.880 --> 15:44.800
John Campbell published the first seven city stories, but he rejected the
eighth. Here Simak tells us of its fate. The first seven were written fairly

15:44.800 --> 16:00.980
well, one after the other. The eighth and final one, John Campbell turned down,
because he said he thought that he'd written it, that he'd published enough of

16:00.980 --> 16:16.520
the City series. And so when he rejected it, I simply threw it up on the shelf,
and figured it was one of my rejects. And then the writer took it down, and I

16:16.520 --> 16:28.300
think I sold it to Amazing Stories. And I don't recall what they called it, but
they put it out with one of their horrible titles.

16:32.380 --> 16:46.980
And then later on, when it came out, it joined the others. The last one was not
published by Campbell. On our next show, we'll talk about a ninth city story.

16:54.360 --> 17:02.520
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
