18:14.820 --> 18:16.560
And here are your hosts.

18:21.000 --> 18:29.540
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Science Fiction writer Clifford Simak's
most famous work is his story collection, City. This collection of eight

18:29.540 --> 18:38.540
connected short stories was first published as a body by Gnome in 1952. Years
afterward, Simak was persuaded to write a ninth city story, Epilog. Here he

18:38.540 --> 18:52.880
explains its genesis. Well, John Campbell died. And, of course, all of us, all of
us were stricken by his death, because he was a comparable young man and

18:52.880 --> 18:55.420
appeared to be in good physical condition.

18:58.040 --> 19:08.180
Some of the writers reverenced him. I'm not too
sure I reverenced him, but I felt very kindly to him. It was very badly hit by

19:08.180 --> 19:25.200
his death. And a group of writers got together and said we'd have to put out a
memorial to John Campbell. And the best way to do it would be to put out the

19:25.200 --> 19:41.140
last issue of the old Astoning story. Not Analog, but the old Astoning stories.
And so they asked, well, I suppose there were a dozen or so people who had

19:41.140 --> 19:56.360
written for the old Astounding stories to write a story for the memorial volume. And
Harry Harrison, who was the editor, phoned me and he said, Cliff, if you will

19:56.360 --> 19:59.060
write a story, I wish you'd write another City story.

20:02.140 --> 20:17.080
And I was reluctant to do that. I shied away from it because it had been quite a
number of years since I'd written the City story. And I knew that I was a

20:17.080 --> 20:22.380
changed writer. I was not the same man as I was when I'd written the stories.

20:25.000 --> 20:37.920
I worried a great deal about the propriety of writing another City story because
I figured that the last one, the last of the day, had wound up the story of the

20:37.920 --> 20:49.180
Webster family and that there was no need of going further. But the more I
thought about it, the more I began to see that if I was going to write something

20:49.180 --> 21:05.580
for that memorial volume, it should be a City story. So for the first time since
I'd written them, I took down my copy of the book City and reread it, trying to

21:05.580 --> 21:20.480
catch the flavor and the spirit of the stories. And when I read the stories, I
simply absolutely ached to rewrite them again because there are some awful

21:20.480 --> 21:31.220
crudities in them. But I knew even as I thought about that, that I couldn't do
it because if I rewrote them, they wouldn't be the City series.

21:33.380 --> 21:50.640
So I sat down and did my best to try to recreate the flavor of the other eight
stories. I think I came very close to it, but not as satisfactorily as I might

21:50.640 --> 22:01.660
have wanted to. Ace published the nine stories as a group for the first time in
1981. The robots in City are gentle, respectful entities. We asked Simak why he

22:01.660 --> 22:24.260
made them so. Most of the writers who had written robots before wrote of them as
machines. And I wrote of them as surrogate human beings. I made them people with

22:24.260 --> 22:36.700
some of the biases and practices that the living human would have stripped away
from them. And I tried to make them the kind of people that I would want to live

22:36.700 --> 22:39.820
with. More on Clifford Simak on our next show.

22:47.320 --> 22:55.420
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

22:55.420 --> 23:03.440
Odessa, Texas. 

