24:12.760 --> 24:20.560
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. Science fiction author Clifford Simak has
been writing for more than 50 years. All his work, especially the well-known

24:20.560 --> 24:30.300
pieces such as City, A Choice of Gods, and Way Station, is characterized by a
warm sentimental flavor that never cloys. Simak's Midwestern roots and values

24:30.300 --> 24:41.700
are evident in his work, and the reader is caught by their charm. We asked Simak
if he purposely worked his philosophy into his works. A man's philosophy is so

24:41.700 --> 24:55.040
much a part of him that he probably doesn't stop and think about it very often.
He doesn't say, well, this is, I'm writing this way because this is the way I

24:55.040 --> 25:05.800
think, or this is the way I feel. When you sit down and write, you're writing
the way you think and you feel unconsciously,

25:08.200 --> 25:11.060
without, without, uh, trying to work at it.

25:19.940 --> 25:29.040
Not all of Simak's characters are model citizens, but none are ever terribly
evil. We ask Simak why evil plays so small a role in his work. I think I've

25:29.040 --> 25:52.700
never been aware of evil. I have been aware of friendship and love and, um, good
fellowship and honesty, truth. I, um, I, um, get very concerned at times about

25:52.700 --> 26:05.680
the condition of the world, not only now, but in times past. And I know that
there is evil. But, uh, but it's, I, I kept it at times, like, not consciously,

26:06.060 --> 26:18.800
but, uh, simply because I didn't want, I guess I didn't want to think about it.
I, um, I concentrated on, as I said before, on the things that seemed important

26:18.800 --> 26:19.240
to me.

26:27.120 --> 26:37.260
Did Simak ever dream, back in his early writing days, that science fiction would
become a fixture in commercial literature? No, not at all. Never for a moment.

26:37.500 --> 26:54.040
We were working in the ghetto. Um, there were very few of us. Uh, science
fiction was read by only a handful. When you met somebody and they found out you

26:54.040 --> 27:06.400
were a science fiction writer, they'd say, how'd you get those crazy ideas? I,
uh, went thinking around, hoping nobody would notice you. Um, you, you were, you

27:06.400 --> 27:20.840
were the bottom of the heap. There's no question about it. You were much more
despicable than maybe the pornographic writers of today. Um, but we kept at it

27:20.840 --> 27:36.160
because we liked it. Because I think, I, I think it, after a few years of it, I
began to feel that probably it would develop and it might have a future. But I

27:36.160 --> 27:51.140
never dreamed that we would be putting out as great, as great and good a
progress as we have. How does Simak want to be remembered as a writer? I don't

27:51.140 --> 28:09.800
know if I will be remembered. But if I am to be remembered as a writer, I'd like
to be remembered as someone who wrote honestly and who is more concerned with

28:09.800 --> 28:13.540
the heart and mind of humanity than with humanity's achievements.

28:21.000 --> 28:25.780
Clifford Simak, a writer whose gentle stories have charmed readers for over 50
years.

